  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Agreements\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate to investigate and prosecute money laundering\n- Sharing of financial intelligence\n- Extradition agreements\n\n3. Compliance Mechanisms\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n\n4. Regulatory Frameworks\n- Common standards for financial institutions\n- Cross-border transaction monitoring\n- Sanctions and penalties\n\n5. Enforcement Cooperation\n- Joint investigations\n- Information exchange between financial intelligence units\n- Coordinated legal actions\n\n6. Technology and Data Sharing\n- Enhanced digital tracking of financial transactions\n- Global financial crime databases\n- Advanced analytics and AI monitoring\n\n7. Jurisdictional Challenges\n- Differences in legal definitions\n- Varying levels of regulatory enforcement\n- Complex international financial networks\n\nThese intersections aim to create a comprehensive, coordinated approach to preventing and detecting money laundering across different national legal systems.",
